14.4 12.6 42.5 30.2 Jun 0.5 15.1 12.8 44.9 26.6 Jul 0.3 14.3 9.8 44.5 31.0 Aug 0.5 20.9 17.7 42.1 18.9 Sep 0.6 28.4 20.3 40.1 10.5 Oct 0.5 26.0 12.9 46.7 13.9 Nov 0.6 26.3 17.0 43.6 12.5 Cabinet Support Rate Remains High The Hosokawa cabinet still maintains a high level of public support four months after its inauguration. Under the LDP ruling, the cabinet support rate moved in parallel with the LDP support rate. However, under the Hosokawa administration, the popularity of the JNP and the coalition parties is in decline while the administration itself receives broad support. In other words, high public support for the cabinet is due to Hosokawa's personal popularity. The LDP support rate remains at 22 percent, or the lowest level since the beginning of the survey. Only farmers, fishermen, and those over 60 years in age offered support of over 30 percent. Support for LDP President Yohei Kono is also dropping. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Table 5. Do you feel you are living in comfort compared with the same period | |in the previous year? (indicated in percents) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Yes |No Change |No | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |3.5 |57.9 |38.1 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- [Text]Changes in Livelihood After the inauguration of the Hosokawa administration, a larger proportion of the public feel more satisfied about politics; however, changes in people's livelihood are not favorable. During the period from January 1991 to September 1993, people did not feel the influence of the recession. However, since October a greater number of pollees began to answer that their living conditions were "becoming worse." If things are left as they are, the Hosokawa administration may lose its popularity. This reminds me of former U.S. President George Bush's failure to win reelection. He had the support of 90 percent of the public immediately after the Gulf war, but the support rate dropped quickly due to the recession. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Table 6. What should the Hosokawa cabinet do if it fails to enact the politi-| |cal reform bills during the ongoing Diet session? (indicated in percents) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |The cabinet should resign en masse |20.6 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |The cabinet should dissolve the lower |26.4 | |house | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |No need for any reaction |37.7 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Other/Don't Know |15.4 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Political Reform and the Hosokawa Cabinet's Responsibility During a news conference immediately after his inauguration, Prime Minister Hosokawa said: "I will take responsibility if I fail to enact the political reform bills during the ongoing Diet session." But the voters are not strict about Hosokawa's responsibility for the political reform issue. In our survey, only 21 percent said "the cabinet should resign en masse to take responsibility." On the other hand, 26 percent said "the cabinet should dissolve the lower house, and 38 percent said "neither the cabinet's resignation nor the lower house's dissolution is needed." ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Table 7. If general elections are held today, which party would you vote for?| | (indicated in percents) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Party |Nov 93 |Nov 92 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |LDP |25.0 |31.0 | ----------------------